library(forcats)
URL <- "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_countries_by_percentage_of_population_living_in_poverty"
webpage <- read_html(URL)
#pagetree <- htmlTreeParse(webpage, useInternalNodes = TRUE)
raw.df <- html_nodes(webpage, "table") %>% .[[1]] %>% html_table(fill = TRUE) %>% as.data.frame() %>% rename_with(~ gsub('(\\[.*?\\])', '', .x))

country_df <- pivot_longer(raw.df, cols = 2:4, names_to = 'live_per_day_level', values_to = 'percentage', values_drop_na = TRUE)
# check any NAs
colSums(is.na(country_df))
##            Country               Year          Continent live_per_day_level 
##                  0                  0                  0                  0 
##         percentage 
##                  0
# factor live_per_day_level
country_df$live_per_day_level <- as.factor(country_df$live_per_day_level)
# find a weird value with[11] at row 190 and use regex to convert to numeric
country_df$percentage <- gsub("(%|\\[.*?\\])", "", country_df$percentage)
country_df$percentage <- as.numeric(country_df$percentage)
colSums(is.na(country_df))
##            Country               Year          Continent live_per_day_level 
##                  0                  0                  0                  0 
##         percentage 
##                  0
levels(as.factor(country_df$Continent))
## [1] "Africa"        "Asia"          "Asia, Europe"  "Europe"       
## [5] "North America" "Oceania"       "South America"
summary_5.5 <- country_df %>% filter(live_per_day_level =="< $5.50") %>% group_by(Continent) %>% summarize(avg_5.50_percentage=mean(percentage), sd_5.50_percentage=sd(percentage))
summary_5.5$avg_5.50_percentage %>% quantile()
##        0%       25%       50%       75%      100% 
##  5.456098 15.236538 28.128571 46.828254 75.204000
# Most African countries have much higher percentage poverty level; oceania is next with around 55% poverty level; asia is about 40% poverty level but with higher standard deviation meaning the variation is more obvious; North America is about 30% and comparatively speaking having medium level poverty level calculated as 50% quantile. In contrast, Europe has a lowest poverty level, and much lower standard deviation. The continent Asia, Europe only consists of 2 countries so the data is not too convincing(sample size is smaller compared with other continents). It seems have low poverty level as well as small standard deviaation.

Q3

top.10.5.5.perc <- country_df %>% filter(live_per_day_level =="< $5.50") %>% select(Country, Continent, percentage) %>% arrange(desc(percentage)) %>% top_n(10)
## Selecting by percentage
top.10.5.5.perc %>% mutate(Country = fct_reorder(as.factor(Country), percentage, .desc = TRUE)) %>% ggplot(aes(x = Country, y = percentage)) + geom_bar(aes(fill = Continent), stat = "identity") +
  labs(x = "Country", y = "percentage", title = "Percentage of Population live less than $5.50 a day") +
  scale_fill_discrete(name = "Continent") +
  coord_flip()

## It is obvious most countries are from Africa in top 10 from population spenidng less than $5.50

Q4

lowest.5.5.5.perc <- country_df %>% filter(live_per_day_level =="< $5.50") %>% select(Country, Continent, percentage) %>% arrange(percentage) %>% head(5)

lowest.5.5.5.perc$Country <- as.vector(lowest.5.5.5.perc$Country)

country_df %>% filter(Country %in% lowest.5.5.5.perc$Country) %>% select(-2) %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = Country, y = percentage)) + geom_bar(aes(fill = live_per_day_level), stat = "identity", position = "dodge") +
  labs(x = "Country", y = "percentage") +
  scale_fill_discrete(name = "live_per_day_level")

# lowest 5 countries are Cyprus, Finland, Slovenia, Swiss, US. By comparing with each country, Finland has contains all 3 groups with same percentage, Cypurus has 2, Slovenia has 1, while US and Swiss do not qualify such groupings.

Q5

country_df %>% filter(Continent %in% c("Europe", "Asia")) %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = live_per_day_level, y = percentage)) +
  geom_boxplot(aes(color = live_per_day_level)) +
  facet_wrap(~ Continent)

## comparing asia with Europe, there exists many areas of distinctions. First of all, the distribution of percentage in asia is much spread than europe.The range per group in asia differs quite a bit, 0- 10% for < $1.90, 0-50% for < $3.20, and 0-90% for < $5.50 while each group in europe remains in a similar pattern. Secondly, there are couple of outliers for asia and europe except < $5.50 for asia. 
## Comparing each group within asia, for < $1.90 and < $3.20 the median is smaller than mean and they exhibit right skew while < $5.50 exhibits left skew where median is larger than mean.
